snippet.textDisplay: yeah this isn’t a problem of individual responsibility, im sorry, expecting people to act rationally about this is the wrong approach, as it feeds into our current economic system, one that assumes humans will always act rationally and forces people to go work in crises like these, etc.... this is much more a structural issue with our global hegemonic neoliberal society, and the expectations of individual responsibility that it assumes. why is it that we don’t have enough hospitals to house people, why is it we aren’t economically prepared to deal with a catastrophic event of this size? these are questions that an “individual responsibility” approach can’t really tackle.

May you leave the world a better place then in which you found

snippet.textDisplay: I don't think people should go to hospitals or get tested unless they have severe symptoms. Save hospital beds and tests for people who really need it. I think going to the hospital to get tested with mild or no symptoms bumps up the risk of contracting more virus particles. When I saw videos of over crowded hospitals in China, where people were trying to get tested, my first concern was the people with mild symptoms exposing themselves to stronger symptoms. If the case is mild enough, the body could fight it off on its own but if it's close to a stronger case, it would have a more difficult time. It's important to know if you have the virus or not but if you're showing no symptoms, you’re not going to be hospitalized. I think it's best for the doctors and nurses to focus their energy on people who have severe cases so they can figure out how to ease the symptoms and cure the virus. They can't do it effectively if their attention is taken away for mild cases. Space and energy is a limited resource. It should be distributed accordingly. Social distancing is effective but overcrowded hospitals are incredibly risky.
